# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: epidemiology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A severe outbreak of cholera occurred in 1854 near Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Golden Square in Soho, London, England, during the worldwide 1846–1860 cholera pandemic.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The outbreak (also known as **Golden Square outbreak**), which killed 616 people, is best known for the physician John Snow's study of its causes and his hypothesis that germ-contaminated water was the cause, rather than something in the air called "miasma".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This discovery influenced public health and the construction of improved sanitation facilities beginning in the mid-19th century.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Later, the term "focus of infection" was used to describe sites, such as the Broad Street pump, where conditions are favourable for transmission of infection.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow unknowingly took advantage of a natural experiment during his endeavours to identify the cause of cholera transmission.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In the mid-19th century, Soho in London had a serious problem with filth due to a large influx of people and lack of proper sanitary services: the London sewer system had not reached Soho.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cowsheds, slaughterhouses and grease-boiling dens lined the streets and contributed animal droppings, rotting fluids and other contaminants to Soho's primitive sewer system.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many cellars had cesspools beneath their floorboards, which formed from the sewers and filth seeping in from outside.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] With the cesspools overrunning, London's government decided to dump the waste into the River Thames, contaminating the water supply.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] London had already had a "series of debilitating cholera outbreaks".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] These included outbreaks in 1832 and 1849, which killed 14,137 people.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time of the Broad Street outbreak, physicians and scientists held two competing theories on the causes of cholera in the human body: miasma theory and germ theory.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London medical community debated the cause of the city's persistent cholera outbreaks.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera-causing bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* was isolated in 1854, but the finding became well known and accepted only decades later.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists concluded that cholera was caused by particles in the air, or "miasmata", which arose from decomposing matter or other dirty organic sources.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "Miasma" particles were thought to travel through the air and infect individuals, and thus cause cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr William Farr, the commissioner for the 1851 London census and a member of the General Register's Office, believed that miasma arose from the soil surrounding the River Thames.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It contained decaying organic matter which contained miasmatic particles and was released into the London air.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists believed in "cleansing and scouring, rather than through the purer scientific approach of microbiology".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Farr later agreed with Snow's germ theory following Snow's publications.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In contrast, the germ theory held that the principal cause of cholera was a germ cell that had not yet been identified.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow theorised that this unknown germ was transmitted from person to person by individuals ingesting water.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] John Simon, a pathologist and London's lead medical officer, called Snow's germ theory "peculiar".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Even though Simon understood Snow's theory, he questioned its relation to the cause of cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] On 31 August 1854, after several other outbreaks elsewhere in the city, there was a major outbreak of cholera in Soho.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Over the next three days, 127 people on or near Broad Street died.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the next week, three quarters of the residents had fled the area.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By 10 September, more than 500 people had died and the mortality rate was 12.8 per thousand inhabitants in some parts of the city.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By the end of the outbreak, 616 people had died.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many of the victims were taken to the Middlesex Hospital, where their treatment was superintended by Florence Nightingale, who briefly joined the hospital in early September in order to help with the outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to a letter by Elizabeth Gaskell, Nightingale "was up night and day from Friday afternoon (Sept.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] 1) to Sunday afternoon, receiving the poor creatures (chiefly fallen women of that neighbourhood - they had it the worst) who were being constantly brought in - - undressing them - putting on turpentine stupes, et cetera, doing it herself to as many as she could manage".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By talking to local residents (with the help of Reverend Henry Whitehead), Snow identified the outbreak's source as the public water pump on Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) at Cambridge Street.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Although Snow's chemical and microscope examination of a sample of the water from this Broad Street pump water did not conclusively prove its danger, the patterns of illness and death among residents in Soho persuaded the St James parish authorities to disable the pump by removing its handle.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow later used a dot map to illustrate how cases of cholera occurred around this pump.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] His efforts to connect the incidence of cholera with potential geographic sources was based on what is now known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He mapped the individual water pumps and generated cells representing all the points on his map that were closest to each pump.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The section of Snow's map representing areas in the city where the closest available source of water was the Broad Street pump had the highest incidence of cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] There was one significant anomaly: none of the workers in the nearby Broad Street brewery contracted cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As they were given a daily allowance of beer, they did not consume water from the nearby well.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the brewing process, the wort (un-fermented beer) is boiled in part so that hops can be added.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This step killed the cholera bacteria in the water they used to brew with, making it safe to drink.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow showed that the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company was taking water from sewage-polluted sections of the Thames and delivering it to homes, resulting in an increased incidence of cholera among its customers.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's study is part of the history of public health and health geography.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It is regarded as the founding event of epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It was discovered later that this public well had been dug 3 feet (0.9 m) from an old cesspit that had begun to leak faecal bacteria.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Waste water from washing nappies used by a baby who had contracted cholera from another source drained into this cesspit.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Its opening was under a nearby house that had been rebuilt further away after a fire and a street widening.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time there were cesspits under most homes.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Most families tried to have their raw sewage collected and dumped in the Thames to prevent their cesspit from filling faster than the sewage could decompose into the soil.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the same time, an investigation of cholera transmission was being conducted in Deptford.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Around 90 people died within a few days in that town, where the water was known to be clean, and there had been no previous outbreaks of cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was informed that the water had recently turned impure.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Before using it, residents had to let it run until the sudsy, sewer-like water turned clear.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow, finding that the water the residents were using was no different from the usual water from their pump, determined that the outbreak must be caused by a leak in the pipes that allowed surrounding sewage and its contaminants to seep in to the water supply.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This was similar to the Broad Street outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The incoming water was being contaminated by the increasing levels of sewage, coupled with lack of safe plumbing.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] After the cholera epidemic subsided, government officials replaced the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They had responded only to the urgent threat posed to the population, and afterwards they rejected Snow's theory.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] To accept his proposal would have meant indirectly accepting the oral-faecal method of transmission of disease, which was too unpleasant for most of the public to contemplate.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Broad Street outbreak was an effect rather than a cause of the epidemic.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's conclusions were not predominantly based on the Broad Street outbreak, as he noted that he hesitated to come to a conclusion based on a population that had predominantly fled the neighbourhood and redistributed itself.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He feared throwing off results of the study.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] From a mathematical perspective, Snow's innovation was focusing on death rates in areas served by two water companies that drew water from the Thames, rather than basing it on data from victims of the Broad Street pump (which drew water from a well).
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work also led to a far greater health and safety impact than the removal of the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Deactivating the pump "hardly made a dent in the citywide cholera epidemic, which went on to claim nearly 3,000 lives".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was sceptical of the prevailing miasma theory, which held that diseases such as cholera or the Black Death were caused by pollution or a noxious form of "bad air".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The germ theory was not yet established (Louis Pasteur proposed it in 1861).
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow did not understand the mechanism by which disease was transmitted, but the evidence led him to believe that it was not foul air.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Based on the pattern of illness among residents, he hypothesized that cholera was spread by an agent in contaminated water.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He first published his theory in 1849, in an essay titled "On the Mode of Communication of Cholera".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1855 he published a second edition, including a more elaborate investigation of the effect of the water supply in the 1854 Soho outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera epidemic of 1849–1854 was also related to the water supplied by companies in London at the time.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The main players were the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company and the Lambeth Waterworks Company.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Both provided water to their customers drawn from the Thames, which was highly contaminated with visible and invisible products and bacteria.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Arthur Hill Hassall examined the filtered water and found it contained animal hair, among other foul substances.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Other companies, such as the New River Company and Chelsea Waterworks Company, were observed to have better filtered water; few deaths occurred in the neighbourhoods they supplied.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They not only obtained their water from cleaner sources than the Thames, but filtered the water and treated it until there were no obvious contaminants.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As mentioned above, Snow is known for his influence on public health, which arose after his studies of the cholera epidemic.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In attempting to figure out who was receiving impure water in each neighbourhood, what is now known as a double-blind experiment fell right into his lap.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow went on to study the water contents from each home through a test performed on each sample.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In this way, it could be deduced from which supplier the home received its water.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that it was indeed impure water from the big companies that allowed cholera to spread rapidly.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He proved this by observing London prisons, finding that cholera ceased there only a few days after switching to cleaner water sources.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's analysis of cholera and cholera outbreaks extended past the closure of the Broad Street pump.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that cholera was transmitted through and affected the alimentary canal within the human body.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cholera did not affect either the circulatory or the nervous system and there was no "poison in the blood...in the consecutive fever...the blood became poisoned from urea getting into the circulation".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, this "urea" entered the blood through kidney failure.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Therefore, the fever was caused by kidney failure, not by a poison already present in the subject's bloodstream.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Popular medical practices, such as bloodletting, could not be effective in such a case.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow also argued that cholera was not a product of Miasma.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "There was nothing in the air to account for the spread of cholera".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, cholera was spread by persons ingesting a substance, not through atmospheric transmittal.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Reverend Henry Whitehead was an assistant curate at St.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Luke's church in Soho during the 1854 cholera outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A former believer in the miasma theory of disease, Whitehead worked to disprove false theories.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was influenced by Snow's theory that cholera spreads by consumption of water contaminated by human waste.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work, particularly his maps of the Soho area cholera victims, convinced Whitehead that the Broad Street pump was the source of the local infections.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead joined Snow in tracking the contamination to a faulty cesspool and the outbreak's index case (the baby with cholera).
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead's work with Snow combined demographic study with scientific observation, setting an important precedent for epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London Board of Health, which had recently been given new powers and was presided over by Sir Benjamin Hall, a Cabinet Minister, had several committees, of which the Committee for Scientific Inquiries was placed in charge of investigating the cholera outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They were to study the atmospheric environment in London and to examine samples of water from several London water companies.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The committee found that the most contaminated water supply came from the South London water companies, Southwark and Vauxhall.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of the Committee for Scientific Inquiries, Richard Dundas Thomson and Arthur Hill Hassall examined what Thomson called "vibriones".
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Thomson examined the occurrence of vibriones in air samples from various cholera wards and Hassall observed vibriones in water samples.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Neither identified vibriones as the cause of cholera.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of its investigation of the cholera epidemic, the Board of Health sent physicians to examine in detail the conditions of the Golden Square neighbourhood and its inhabitants.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Board of Health ultimately attributed the 1854 epidemic to miasma.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Edwin Lankester was a physician on the local research conglomerate that studied the 1854 Broad Street cholera epidemic.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1866, Lankester wrote about Snow's conclusion that the pump caused the outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He agreed with Snow at the time, but his opinion, like Snow's, was not publicly supported.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Lankester subsequently closed the pump due to Snow's theory and data on the pattern of infection, and infection rates dropped significantly.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was eventually named the first medical officer of health for St James's parish in London, the area where the pump was.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A replica pump was installed in 1992 at the site of the 1854 pump.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Every year the John Snow Society holds "Pumphandle Lectures" on public health subjects.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Until 2015, when the pump was removed due to redevelopment, it also held a ceremony there in which it removed and reattached the pump handle to commemorate Snow's discovery.
[src:epidemiology/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The pump's original location is marked by a red granite paver, and plaques at the John Snow pub at the corner describe Snow's findings.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The key event at the conference was the presentation of data from the Vaccine Safety Datalink examining the possibility of a link between the mercury compound thimerosol in vaccines and neurological problems in children who had received those vaccines.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy, Jr., published by *Rolling Stone* and Salon.com, focused on the Simpsonwood meeting as part of a conspiracy to withhold or falsify vaccine-safety information.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] However, Kennedy's article contained numerous major factual errors and, after a number of corrections, was ultimately retracted by Salon.com.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Nonetheless, on the basis of Kennedy's claims, the conference gained notoriety in the anti-vaccination movement.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The conference was convened following a resolution by the Congress of the United States in 1997 requiring the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to review the thimerosal content of approved drugs and biologics.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Three vaccines of primary interest were discussed: hepatitis B vaccine, DPT vaccine, and the Hib vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Attendees included experts in the fields of autism, pediatrics, toxicology, epidemiology and vaccines.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Also in attendance were approximately half a dozen public-health organisations and pharmaceutical companies, as well as eleven consultants to the CDC, a rapporteur, and a statistician.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The meeting served as a prelude to vaccine policy meetings held by the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP), which sets U.S. vaccine policy for the CDC.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The session was also to serve as the initial meeting of the ACIP work group on thimerosal and immunization.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Presentations and supporting documents from the conference were subject to a news embargo until June 21, 2000, at which point they were published by the ACIP.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] After the conference, researchers carried out a planned second phase to further analyze and clarify the study's preliminary findings.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The results of this second analysis were published in 2003.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The June 20, 2005, issue of *Rolling Stone* contained an article written by Robert F.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy, Jr., entitled "Deadly Immunity".
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The article, which was also published on Salon.com, focused on the Simpsonwood conference, and alleged that government and private industry had colluded to "thwart the Freedom of Information Act" and "withhold" vaccine-safety findings from the public.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Salon.com later said that the errors in the article "went far in undermining Kennedy’s exposé", and corrected it on five occasions.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The publisher later retracted it in January 2011, stating that criticisms of the article and flaws in the science connecting autism and vaccines undermined its value.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] By the time the final study results discussed at Simpsonwood were published in 2003, the lead researcher, Thomas Verstraeten, had gone to work for GlaxoSmithKline.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy contended that the delay in publication gave Verstraeten sufficient time to fix the data around the CDC's alleged objective of obscuring a link between thimerosal and autism.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Verstraeten denied the allegations, and published an account of the matter in the journal *Pediatrics*.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions rejected allegations of impropriety against Verstraeten and the CDC.
[src:epidemiology/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Addressing Kennedy's statements, the Committee found that: "Instead of hiding the [Simpsonwood] data or restricting access to it, CDC distributed it, often to individuals who had never seen it before, and solicited outside opinion regarding how to interpret it.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The **2009 swine flu pandemic vaccines** were influenza vaccines developed to protect against the pandemic H1N1/09 virus.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] These vaccines either contained inactivated (killed) influenza virus, or weakened live virus that could not cause influenza.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The killed virus was injected, while the live virus was given as a nasal spray.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Both these types of vaccine were produced by growing the virus in chicken eggs.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Around three billion doses were produced, with delivery in November 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In studies, the vaccines appeared both effective and safe, providing a strong protective immune response and having a similar safety profile to the usual seasonal influenza vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, about 30% of people already had some immunity to the virus, with the vaccine conferring greatest benefit on young people, since many older people are already immune through exposure to similar viruses in the past.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccine also provided some cross-protection against the 1918 flu pandemic strain.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Developing, testing, and manufacturing sufficient quantities of a vaccine is a process that takes many months.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] TIV works by putting into the bloodstream those parts of three strains of flu virus that the body uses to create antibodies; while LAIV works by inoculating the body with those same three strains, but in a modified form that cannot cause illness.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] LAIV is not recommended for individuals under age 2 or over age 49, but might be comparatively more effective among children over age two.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] For the inactivated vaccines, the virus is grown by injecting it, along with some antibiotics, into fertilized chicken eggs.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] About one to two eggs are needed to make each dose of vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The virus replicates within the allantois of the embryo, which is the equivalent of the placenta in mammals.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The fluid in this structure is removed and the virus purified from this fluid by methods such as filtration or centrifugation.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The purified viruses are then inactivated ("killed") with a small amount of a disinfectant.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The inactivated virus is treated with detergent to break up the virus into particles, and the broken capsule segments and released proteins are concentrated by centrifugation.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The final preparation is suspended in sterile phosphate buffered saline ready for injection.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This vaccine mainly contains the killed virus but might also contain tiny amounts of egg protein and the antibiotics, disinfectant and detergent used in the manufacturing process.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In multi-dose versions of the vaccine, the preservative thimerosal is added to prevent growth of bacteria.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In some versions of the vaccine used in Europe and Canada, such as *Arepanrix* and *Fluad*, an adjuvant is also added, this contains squalene, vitamin E and an emulsifier called polysorbate 80.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] To make the live vaccine, the virus is first adapted to grow at 25 °C (77 °F) and then grown at this temperature until it loses the ability to cause illness in humans, which requires the virus to grow at normal human body temperature of 37 °C (99 °F).
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Multiple mutations are needed for the virus to grow at cold temperatures, so this process is effectively irreversible and once the virus has lost virulence (become "attenuated"), it will not regain the ability to infect people.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The attenuated virus is then grown in chicken eggs as before.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The virus-containing fluid is harvested and the virus purified by filtration; this step also removes any contaminating bacteria.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The filtered preparation is then diluted into a solution that stabilizes the virus.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This solution contains monosodium glutamate, potassium phosphate, gelatin, the antibiotic gentamicin, and sugar.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A different method of producing influenza virus was used to produce the Novartis vaccine Optaflu.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In this vaccine the virus is grown in cell culture instead of in eggs.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This method is faster than the classic egg-based system and produces a purer final product.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There are no traces of egg proteins in the final product, so it is safe for people with egg allergies.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Prior to the H1N1/09 outbreak, WHO recommended that vaccines for the Northern Hemisphere's 2009–2010 flu season contain an A(H1N1)-like virus, and stocks were made available.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, the strain of H1N1 in the seasonal flu vaccine was different from the pandemic strain H1N1/09 and offered no immunity against it.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) characterized over 80 new H1N1 viruses that may be used in a vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Seasonal flu vaccine was being made as of May 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Although vaccine makers would be ready to switch to making a swine flu vaccine, many questions remained unanswered, including: "Should we really make a swine flu vaccine?
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Should we base a vaccine on the current virus, since flu viruses change rapidly?
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Vaccine against the current virus might be far less effective against a changed virus – should we wait to see if the virus changes?
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The costs of producing a vaccine also became an issue, with some U.S. lawmakers questioning whether a new vaccine was worth the unknown benefits.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Representatives Phil Gingrey and Paul Broun, for instance, were not convinced that the U.S. should spend up to US$2 billion to produce one, with Gingrey stating "We can't let all of our spending and our reaction be media-driven in responding to a panic so that we don't get Katrina-ed. ...
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Before the pandemic was declared, the WHO said that if a pandemic was declared it would attempt to make sure that a substantial amount of vaccine was available for the benefit of developing countries.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Vaccine makers and countries with standing orders, such as the U.S. and a number of European countries, would be asked, according to WHO officials, "to share with developing countries from the moment the first batches are ready if an H1N1 vaccine is made" for a pandemic strain.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The global body stated that it wanted companies to donate at least 10% of their production or offer reduced prices for poor countries that could otherwise be left without vaccines if there is a sudden surge in demand.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] After a meeting with the WHO on 14 May 2009, pharmaceutical companies said they were ready to begin making a swine flu vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to news reports, the WHO's experts would present recommendations to WHO Director-General Margaret Chan, who was expected to issue advice to vaccine manufacturers and the Sixty-second World Health Assembly.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] WHO's Keiji Fukuda told reporters "These are enormously complicated questions, and they are not something that anyone can make in a single meeting." Most flu vaccine companies can not make both seasonal flu vaccine and pandemic flu vaccine at the same time.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Production takes months and it is impossible to switch halfway through if health officials make a mistake.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] If the swine flu mutates, scientists aren't sure how effective a vaccine made now from the current strain will remain.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Rather than wait on the WHO decision, however, some countries in Europe have decided to go ahead with early vaccine orders.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] On 20 May 2009, AP reported: "Manufacturers won't be able to start making the [swine flu] vaccine until mid-July at the earliest, weeks later than previous predictions, according to an expert panel convened by WHO.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] It will then take months to produce the vaccine in large quantities.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Another option proposed by the CDC was an "earlier rollout of seasonal vaccine," according to the CDC's Daniel Jernigan.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] He said the CDC would work with vaccine manufacturers and experts to see if that would be possible and desirable.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Flu vaccination usually starts in September in the United States and peaks in November.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some vaccine experts agree it would be better to launch a second round of vaccinations against the new H1N1 strain instead of trying to add it to the seasonal flu vaccine or replacing one of its three components with the new H1N1 virus.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The Australian company CSL said that they were developing a vaccine for the swine flu and predicted that a suitable vaccine would be ready by August.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, John Sterling, Editor in Chief of *Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology News*, said on 2 June, "It can take five or six months to come up with an entirely novel influenza vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of September 2009, a vaccine for H1N1/09 was expected to be available starting in November 2009, with production of three billion doses per year.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] It was expected that two doses would be needed to provide sufficient protection, but tests indicated that one dose would be sufficient for adults.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of 28 September 2009, GlaxoSmithKline produced a vaccine made by growing the virus in hens' eggs, then breaking and deactivating the virus, and Baxter International produced a vaccine made in cell culture, suitable for those who have an egg allergy.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccines have been approved for use in the European Union.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Initial Phase I human testing began with Novartis' MF59 candidate in July 2009, at which time phase II trials of CSL's candidate CSL425 vaccine were planned to start in August 2009, but had not begun recruiting.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Sanofi Pasteur's candidate inactivated H1N1 had several phase II trials planned as of 21 July 2009, but had not begun recruiting.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] News coverage conflicted with this information, as Australian trials of the CSL candidate were announced as having started on 21 July, and the Chinese government announced the start of trials of the Hualan Biological Engineering candidate.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In July 2009, Omninvest in Hungary, in a randomized-controlled trial, began testing Fluval P, a whole virion, aluminum adjuvanted pandemic influenza H1N1 vaccine, which was found to be safe and effective, when administered alone, or together with the seasonal influenza vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Pandemrix, made by GlaxoSmithKline (GSK), and Focetria, made by Novartis were approved by the European Medicines Agency on 25 September 2009, and Celvapan, made by Baxter was approved the following week.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The first comparative clinical study of both vaccines started on children in the United Kingdom on 25 September 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] GSK announced results from clinical trials assessing the use of Pandemrix in children, adults, and the elderly.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A 2009 trial examined the safety and efficacy of two different doses of the split-virus vaccine, and was published in *The New England Journal of Medicine*.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccine used in the trial was prepared by CSL Biotherapies in chicken eggs, in the same way as the seasonal vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A robust immune response was produced in over 90% of patients after a single dose of either 15 or 30 μg of antigen.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This study suggested that the current recommendation for two doses of vaccine are overkill and that a single dose is quite sufficient.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Arepanrix, an AS03-Adjuvanted H1N1 Pandemic Influenza Vaccine similar to Pandemrix and also made by GSK, was authorized by Canada's Minister of Health on 21 October 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] National Institutes of Health (NIH) concluded that the 2009 H1N1 ("swine flu") vaccine has a safety profile similar to that of seasonal vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In an initial clinical trial in Australia, non-serious adverse events were reported by about half of the 240 people vaccinated, with these events including tenderness and pain at the site of injection, headache, malaise, and muscle pain.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Two people had more severe events, with a much longer spell of nausea, muscle pain and malaise that lasted several days.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The authors stated that the frequency and severity of these adverse events were similar to those normally seen with seasonal influenza vaccines.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A second trial involved 2,200 people ranging from 3 to 77 years of age.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In this study no patients reported serious adverse events, with the most commonly observed events being pain at the injection site and fever, which occurred in 10–25% of people.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Although this trial followed up patients individually, the Government has been criticized for relying on voluntary reporting for post-vaccination evaluation in other circumstances, since this is "unlikely to accurately measure the percentage of people who get adverse effect".
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of 19 November 2009, the World Health Organization (WHO) said that 65 million doses of vaccine had been administered and that it had a similar safety profile to the seasonal flu vaccine, with no significant differences in the adverse events produced by the different types of vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There has been one report of an adverse event per 10,000 doses of vaccine, with only five percent of these adverse events being serious, an overall rate of serious events of one in 200,000 doses.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In Canada, after 6.6 million doses of vaccine had been distributed between 21 October and 7 November, there were reports of mild adverse events in 598 people vaccinated including: nausea, dizziness, headache, fever, vomiting, and swelling or soreness at the injection site.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There were reports of tingling lips or tongue, difficulty breathing, hives, and skin rashes.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Thirty six people had serious adverse events, including anaphylaxis and febrile convulsions.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The rate of serious adverse events is one in 200,000 doses distributed, which according to Canada's chief public health officer, is less than expected for the seasonal flu vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] GlaxoSmithKline recalled a batch of vaccine in Canada after it appeared to cause higher rates of adverse events than other batches.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the USA, 46 million doses had been distributed as of 20 November 2009, and 3182 adverse events were reported.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The CDC stated that the "vast majority" were mild, with about one serious adverse event in 260,000 doses.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In Japan, around 15 million people had been vaccinated by 31 December 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] 1,900 cases of side effects and 104 cases of death were reported from medical institutions.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The health ministry announced that it will conduct epidemiologic investigation.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In France, around five million people had been vaccinated by 30 December 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] 2,657 cases of side effects, eight cases of intrauterine death and five cases of miscarriages were reported after vaccination by afssaps.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Rare potential adverse events are temporary bleeding disorders and Guillain–Barré syndrome (GBS), a serious condition involving the peripheral nervous system, from which most patients recover fully within a few months to a year.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some studies have indicated that influenza-like illness is itself associated with an increased risk of GBS, suggesting that vaccination might indirectly protect against the disorder by protecting against flu.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to Marie-Paule Kieny of WHO assessing the side-effects of large-scale influenza vaccination is complicated by the fact that in any large population a few people will become ill and die at any time.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some scientists have reported concerns about the longer-term effects of the vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] For instance, Sucharit Bhakdi, professor of medical microbiology at the Johannes Gutenberg University of Mainz in Germany, wrote in the journal, *Medical Microbiology and Immunology*, of the possibility that immune stimulation by vaccines or any other cause might worsen pre-existing heart disease.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Chris Shaw, a neuroscientist at the University of British Columbia, expressed concern that serious side-effects may not appear immediately; he said it took five to ten years to see most of the Gulf War syndrome outcomes.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Squalene-based adjuvants have been used in European influenza vaccines since 1997, with about 22 million doses administered over the past twelve years.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The WHO states that no severe side effects have been associated with these vaccines, although they can produce mild inflammation at the site of injection.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The safety of squalene-containing influenza vaccines have also been tested in two separate clinical trials, one with healthy non-elderly people, and one with elderly people, in both trials the vaccine was safe and well tolerated, with only weak side-effects, such as mild pain at the injection site.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A 2009 meta-analysis brought together data from 64 clinical trials of influenza vaccines with the squalene-containing adjuvant MF59 and compared them to the effects of vaccines with no adjuvant.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A paper published in 2000 suggested that squalene might have caused of Gulf War syndrome by producing anti-squalene antibodies, although other scientists stated that it was uncertain if the methods used were actually capable of detecting these antibodies.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Furthermore, none of the vaccines given to US troops during the Gulf war actually contained any squalene adjuvants.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Multi-dose versions of the vaccine contain the preservative thiomersal (also known as thimerosal), a mercury compound that prevents contamination when the vial is used repeatedly.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Single-dose versions and the live vaccine do not contain this preservative.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the U.S., one dose from a multi-dose vial contains approximately 25 micrograms of mercury, a bit less than a typical tuna fish sandwich.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] (The comparison of the injected and ingested quantities is for reference only, since the rate of absorption of ingested elemental mercury into the bloodstream is less than 0.01%.) In Canada, different variants contain five and 50 micrograms of thimerosal per dose.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The use of thiomersal has been controversial, with claims that it can cause autism and other developmental disorders.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Institute of Medicine examined these claims and concluded in 2004 that the evidence did not support any link between vaccines and autism.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] National Health Service stated in 2003 that "There is no evidence of long-term adverse effects due to the exposure levels of thiomersal in vaccines." The World Health Organization concluded that there is "no evidence of toxicity in infants, children or adults exposed to thiomersal in vaccines".
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In 2008 a review noted that even though thiomersal was removed from all US childhood vaccines in 2001, this has not changed the number of autism diagnoses, which are still increasing.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to the CDC, there is no evidence either for or against dystonia being caused by the vaccinations.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Due to the very low numbers of cases, dystonia is poorly understood.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There were only five cases noted that might have been associated with influenza vaccinations over a span of eighteen years.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In one discredited case, a woman wrongly blamed difficulties with movement and speech on a seasonal influenza vaccination.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The Dystonia Medical Research Foundation stated that it is unlikely that the symptoms in this case were actually dystonia and stated that there has "never been a validated case of dystonia resulting from a flu shot".
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A vaccine court special master concluded that the woman's symptoms weren't from the vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] On 15 December 2009, one of the five manufacturers supplying the H1N1 vaccine to the United States recalled thousands of doses because they were not as potent as expected.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The French manufacturer Sanofi Pasteur voluntarily recalled about 800,000 doses of vaccine meant for children between the ages of six months and 35 months.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The company and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) emphasized that the recall was not prompted by safety concerns, and that even though the vaccine is not quite as potent as it is supposed to be, children who received it do not need to be immunized again.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The CDC emphasized that there is no danger for any child who received the recalled vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] When asked what parents should do, CDC spokesman Tom Skinner said, "absolutely nothing." He said if children receive this vaccine, they will be fine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In 2010, The Swedish Medical Products Agency (MPA) and The Finnish National Institute for Health and Welfare (THL) received reports from Swedish and Finnish health care professionals regarding narcolepsy as suspected adverse reaction following Pandemrix flu vaccination.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The reports concern children aged 12–16 years where symptoms compatible with narcolepsy, diagnosed after thorough medical investigation, have occurred one to two months after vaccination.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] THL concluded in February 2011 that there is a clear connection between the Pandemrix vaccination campaign of 2009 and 2010 and narcolepsy epidemic in Finland: there was a nine times higher probability to get narcolepsy with vaccination than without it.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This excludes the large majority of individuals aged six months to 24 years, a group for which the CDC recommends vaccination.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The United Kingdom began its administration program 21 October 2009.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] UK Soldiers serving in Afghanistan will also be offered vaccination.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] By April 2010, it was apparent that most of the vaccine was not needed.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The US government had bought 229 million doses of H1N1 vaccines of which 91 million doses were used; of the surplus, 5 million doses were stored in bulk, 15 million doses were sent to developing countries and 71 million doses were destroyed.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The World Health Organization is planning to examine if it overreacted to the H1N1 outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] General political issues, not restricted to the 2009 outbreak, arose regarding the distribution of vaccine.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the case of a lethal pandemic people will be demanding access to the vaccine and the major problem will be making it available to those who need it.
[src:epidemiology/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] While it has been suggested that compulsory vaccination may be needed to control a pandemic, many countries do not have a legal framework that would allow this.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:epidemiology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] An **academic clinical trial** is a clinical trial not funded by pharmaceutical or biotechnology company for commercial ends but by public-good agencies (usually universities or medical trusts) to advance medicine.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] These trials are a valuable component of the health care system; they benefit patients and help determine the safety and efficacy of drugs and devices, and play an important role in the checks and balances that regular commercially oriented clinical trials.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] A typical area of academic clinical trials is the advancement and optimization of already existing therapies.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] Thus, academic clinical trials may for instance test how a combination of registered drugs may improve treatment outcomes; or they may apply registered treatments in additional, less frequent indications.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] Such research questions are not a primary focus of for-profit companies, and thus these trials are typically initiated by individual investigators or academic research organizations.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] There are many different organizations which have an interest in academic clinical trials and facilitate or take part in their conduct.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] Academic clinical trials are run at academic sites, such as medical schools, academic hospitals, and universities; and non-academic sites which may be managed by so-called site management organizations (SMOs).
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] Site management organizations are for-profit organizations which enlist and manage the physician practice sites that actually recruit and follow patients enrolled in clinical trials.
[src:epidemiology/academic-clinical-trials] In some cases, academic members participate in clinical trials as members of SMOs.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] In the statistical area of survival analysis, an **accelerated failure time model** (**AFT model**) is a parametric model that provides an alternative to the commonly used proportional hazards models.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Whereas a proportional hazards model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to multiply the hazard by some constant, an AFT model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to accelerate or decelerate the life course of a disease by some constant.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] There is strong basic science evidence from *C. elegans* experiments by Stroustrup et al. indicating that AFT models are the correct model for biological survival processes.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] where $\theta$ denotes the joint effect of covariates, typically $\theta =\exp(-[\beta _{1}X_{1}+\cdots +\beta _{p}X_{p}])$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] This is satisfied if the probability density function of the event is taken to be $f(t|\theta )=\theta f_{0}(\theta t)$ ; it then follows for the survival function that $S(t|\theta )=S_{0}(\theta t)$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] From this it is easy to see that the moderated life time T is distributed such that $T\theta$ and the unmoderated life time $T_{0}$ have the same distribution.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] where the last term is distributed as $\log(T_{0})$ , i.e., independently of $\theta$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] This reduces the accelerated failure time model to regression analysis (typically a linear model) where $-\log(\theta )$ represents the fixed effects, and $\epsilon$ represents the noise.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Different distributions of $\epsilon$ imply different distributions of $T_{0}$ , i.e., different baseline distributions of the survival time.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Typically, in survival-analytic contexts, many of the observations are censored: we only know that $T_{i}>t_{i}$ , not $T_{i}=t_{i}$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] In fact, the former case represents survival, while the later case represents an event/death/censoring during the follow-up.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] These right-censored observations can pose technical challenges for estimating the model, if the distribution of $T_{0}$ is unusual.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The interpretation of $\theta$ in accelerated failure time models is straightforward: $\theta =2$ means that everything in the relevant life history of an individual happens twice as fast.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, if the model concerns the development of a tumor, it means that all of the pre-stages progress twice as fast as for the unexposed individual, implying that the expected time until a clinical disease is 0.5 of the baseline time.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, this does not mean that the hazard function $\lambda (t|\theta )$ is always twice as high—that would be the proportional hazards model.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike proportional hazards models, in which Cox's semi-parametric proportional hazards model is more widely used than parametric models, AFT models are predominantly fully parametric i.e. a probability distribution is specified for $\log(T_{0})$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hence, technical developments in this direction would be highly desirable.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] When a frailty term is incorporated in the survival model, the regression parameter estimates from AFT models are robust to omitted covariates, unlike proportional hazards models.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] They are also less affected by the choice of probability distribution for the frailty term.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of AFT models are easily interpreted.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, the results of a clinical trial with mortality as the endpoint could be interpreted as a certain percentage increase in future life expectancy on the new treatment compared to the control.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] So a patient could be informed that he would be expected to live (say) 15% longer if he took the new treatment.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hazard ratios can prove harder to explain in layman's terms.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic distribution provides the most commonly used AFT model.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike the Weibull distribution, it can exhibit a non-monotonic hazard function which increases at early times and decreases at later times.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] It is somewhat similar in shape to the log-normal distribution but it has heavier tails.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic cumulative distribution function has a simple closed form, which becomes important computationally when fitting data with censoring.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] For the censored observations one needs the survival function, which is the complement of the cumulative distribution function, i.e. one needs to be able to evaluate $S(t|\theta )=1-F(t|\theta )$ .
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The Weibull distribution (including the exponential distribution as a special case) can be parameterised as either a proportional hazards model or an AFT model, and is the only family of distributions to have this property.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of fitting a Weibull model can therefore be interpreted in either framework.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, the biological applicability of this model may be limited by the fact that the hazard function is monotonic, i.e. either decreasing or increasing.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Any distribution on a multiplicatively closed group, such as the positive real numbers, is suitable for an AFT model.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Other distributions include the log-normal, gamma, hypertabastic, Gompertz distribution, and inverse Gaussian distributions, although they are less popular than the log-logistic, partly as their cumulative distribution functions do not have a closed form.
[src:epidemiology/accelerated-failure-time-model] Finally, the generalized gamma distribution is a three-parameter distribution that includes the Weibull, log-normal and gamma distributions as special cases.
[src:epidemiology/atc-code-j07] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] It is a cornerstone of public health, and shapes policy decisions and evidence-based practice by identifying risk factors for disease and targets for preventive healthcare.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists help with study design, collection, and statistical analysis of data, amend interpretation and dissemination of results (including peer review and occasional systematic review).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiology has helped develop methodology used in clinical research, public health studies, and, to a lesser extent, basic research in the biological sciences.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Major areas of epidemiological study include disease causation, transmission, outbreak investigation, disease surveillance, environmental epidemiology, forensic epidemiology, occupational epidemiology, screening, biomonitoring, and comparisons of treatment effects such as in clinical trials.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists rely on other scientific disciplines like biology to better understand disease processes, statistics to make efficient use of the data and draw appropriate conclusions, social sciences to better understand proximate and distal causes, and engineering for exposure assessment.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiology, literally meaning 'the study of what is upon the people', is derived from Greek *epi* 'upon, among', *demos* 'people' and *logos* 'study', referring to the study of human populations.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, the term is widely used in studies of zoological populations (veterinary epidemiology), although the term 'epizootiology' was historically used.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] 'Epidemiology' has also been applied to studies of plant populations (botanical or plant disease epidemiology).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The distinction between "epidemic" and "endemic" was first drawn by Hippocrates, The term "epidemiology" appears to have first been used to describe the study of epidemics in 1802 by the Spanish physician Joaquín de Villalba in *Epidemiología Española*.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists also study the interaction of diseases in a population, a condition known as a syndemic.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The term epidemiology is now widely applied to cover the description and causation of not only epidemic, infectious disease, but of disease in general, including related conditions and, especially since the 20th century, chronic diseases such as diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and cancer.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Some examples of topics examined through epidemiology include high blood pressure, mental illness and obesity.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Therefore, this epidemiology is based upon how the pattern of the disease causes change in the function of human beings.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, taught by Democritus, was known as the father of medicine, sought a logic to sickness; he is the first person known to have examined the relationships between the occurrence of disease and environmental influences.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Hippocrates believed sickness of the human body to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors (black bile, yellow bile, blood, and phlegm).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The cure to the sickness was to remove or add the humor in question to balance the body.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This belief led to the application of bloodletting and dieting in medicine.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] He coined the terms *endemic* (for diseases usually found in some places but not in others) and *epidemic* (for diseases that are seen at some times but not others).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In the middle of the 16th century, a doctor from Verona named Girolamo Fracastoro was the first to propose a theory that the very small, unseeable, particles that cause disease were alive.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] They were considered to be able to spread by air, multiply by themselves and to be destroyable by fire.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In this way he refuted Galen's miasma theory (poison gas in sick people).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In 1543 he wrote a book *De contagione et contagiosis morbis*, in which he was the first to promote personal and environmental hygiene to prevent disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The development of a sufficiently powerful microscope by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1675 provided visual evidence of living particles consistent with a germ theory of disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] During the Ming dynasty, Wu Youke (1582–1652) developed the idea that some diseases were caused by transmissible agents, which he called *Li Qi* (戾气 or pestilential factors) when he observed various epidemics rage around him between 1641 and 1644.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] His book *Wen Yi Lun* (瘟疫论, Treatise on Pestilence/Treatise of Epidemic Diseases) can be regarded as the main etiological work that brought forward the concept.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] His concepts were still being considered in analysing SARS outbreak by WHO in 2004 in the context of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Another pioneer, Thomas Sydenham (1624–1689), was the first to distinguish the fevers of Londoners in the later 1600s.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] His theories on cures of fevers met with much resistance from traditional physicians at the time.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] He was not able to find the initial cause of the smallpox fever he researched and treated.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] John Graunt, a haberdasher and amateur statistician, published *Natural and Political Observations ... upon the Bills of Mortality* in 1662.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In it, he analysed the mortality rolls in London before the Great Plague, presented one of the first life tables, and reported time trends for many diseases, new and old.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] He provided statistical evidence for many theories on disease, and also refuted some widespread ideas on them.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] John Snow is famous for his investigations into the causes of the 19th-century cholera epidemics, and is also known as the father of (modern) Epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] He began with noticing the significantly higher death rates in two areas supplied by Southwark Company.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] His identification of the Broad Street pump as the cause of the Soho epidemic is considered the classic example of epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Snow used chlorine in an attempt to clean the water and removed the handle; this ended the outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This has been perceived as a major event in the history of public health and regarded as the founding event of the science of epidemiology, having helped shape public health policies around the world.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, Snow's research and preventive measures to avoid further outbreaks were not fully accepted or put into practice until after his death due to the prevailing Miasma Theory of the time, a model of disease in which poor air quality was blamed for illness.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This was used to rationalize high rates of infection in impoverished areas instead of addressing the underlying issues of poor nutrition and sanitation, and was proven false by his work.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Other pioneers include Danish physician Peter Anton Schleisner, who in 1849 related his work on the prevention of the epidemic of neonatal tetanus on the Vestmanna Islands in Iceland.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Another important pioneer was Hungarian physician Ignaz Semmelweis, who in 1847 brought down infant mortality at a Vienna hospital by instituting a disinfection procedure.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] His findings were published in 1850, but his work was ill-received by his colleagues, who discontinued the procedure.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Disinfection did not become widely practiced until British surgeon Joseph Lister, aided by his colleague, chemist Thomas Anderson, was able to "discover" antiseptics in 1865 based on the earlier work of Louis Pasteur.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In the early 20th century, mathematical methods were introduced into epidemiology by Ronald Ross, Janet Lane-Claypon, Anderson Gray McKendrick, and others.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In 1927, William Ogilvy Kermack and Anderson Gray McKendrick published the foundational SIR (Susceptible-Infected-Recovered) model, applying mass-action kinetics from chemistry to disease transmission in populations.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In a parallel development during the 1920s, German-Swiss pathologist Max Askanazy and others founded the International Society for Geographical Pathology to systematically investigate the geographical pathology of cancer and other non-infectious diseases across populations in different regions.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] After World War II, Richard Doll and other non-pathologists joined the field and advanced methods to study cancer, a disease with patterns and mode of occurrences that could not be suitably studied with the methods developed for epidemics of infectious diseases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Geography pathology eventually combined with infectious disease epidemiology to make the field that is epidemiology today.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Another breakthrough was the 1954 publication of the results of the British Doctors Study, led by Richard Doll and Austin Bradford Hill, which lent very strong statistical support to the link between tobacco smoking and lung cancer.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In the late 20th century, with the advancement of biomedical sciences, a number of molecular markers in blood, other biospecimens and environment were identified as predictors of development or risk of a certain disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiology research to examine the relationship between these biomarkers analyzed at the molecular level and disease was broadly named "molecular epidemiology".
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Specifically, "genetic epidemiology" has been used for epidemiology of germline genetic variation and disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Genetic variation is typically determined using DNA from peripheral blood leukocytes.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Since the 2000s, genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have been commonly performed to identify genetic risk factors for many diseases and health conditions.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] While most molecular epidemiology studies are still using conventional disease diagnosis and classification systems, it is increasingly recognized that disease progression represents inherently heterogeneous processes differing from person to person.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Studies to examine the relationship between an exposure and molecular pathologic signature of disease (particularly cancer) became increasingly common throughout the 2000s.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, the use of molecular pathology in epidemiology posed unique challenges, including lack of research guidelines and standardized statistical methodologies, and paucity of interdisciplinary experts and training programs.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Furthermore, the concept of disease heterogeneity appears to conflict with the long-standing premise in epidemiology that individuals with the same disease name have similar etiologies and disease processes.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In MPE, investigators analyze the relationships between (A) environmental, dietary, lifestyle and genetic factors; (B) alterations in cellular or extracellular molecules; and (C) evolution and progression of disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A better understanding of heterogeneity of disease pathogenesis will further contribute to elucidate etiologies of disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The MPE approach can be applied to not only neoplastic diseases but also non-neoplastic diseases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The concept and paradigm of MPE have become widespread in the 2010s.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] There is increasing recognition that a wide range of modern data sources, many not originating from healthcare or epidemiology, can be used for epidemiological study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Such digital epidemiology can include data from internet searching, mobile phone records and retail sales of drugs.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In observational studies, nature is allowed to "take its course", as epidemiologists observe from the sidelines.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Conversely, in experimental studies, the epidemiologist is the one in control of all of the factors entering a certain case study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiological studies are aimed, where possible, at revealing unbiased relationships between exposures such as alcohol or smoking, biological agents, stress, or chemicals to mortality or morbidity.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The identification of causal relationships between these exposures and outcomes is an important aspect of epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Modern epidemiologists use informatics and infodemiology as tools.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Observational studies have two components, descriptive and analytical.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Descriptive observations pertain to the "who, what, where and when of health-related state occurrence".
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, analytical observations deal more with the 'how' of a health-related event.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Experimental epidemiology contains three case types: randomized controlled trials (often used for a new medicine or drug testing), field trials (conducted on those at a high risk of contracting a disease), and community trials (research on social originating diseases).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The term 'epidemiologic triad' is used to describe the intersection of *Host*, *Agent*, and *Environment* in analyzing an outbreak.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Case-series may refer to the qualitative study of the experience of a single patient, or small group of patients with a similar diagnosis, or to a statistical factor with the potential to produce illness with periods when they are unexposed.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The former type of study is purely descriptive and cannot be used to make inferences about the general population of patients with that disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] These types of studies, in which an astute clinician identifies an unusual feature of a disease or a patient's history, may lead to a formulation of a new hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Using the data from the series, analytic studies could be done to investigate possible causal factors.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] These can include case-control studies or prospective studies.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A case-control study would involve matching comparable controls without the disease to the cases in the series.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A prospective study would involve following the case series over time to evaluate the disease's natural history.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The latter type, more formally described as self-controlled case-series studies, divide individual patient follow-up time into exposed and unexposed periods and use fixed-effects Poisson regression processes to compare the incidence rate of a given outcome between exposed and unexposed periods.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This technique has been extensively used in the study of adverse reactions to vaccination and has been shown in some circumstances to provide statistical power comparable to that available in cohort studies.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Case-control studies select subjects based on their disease status.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A group of individuals that are disease positive (the "case" group) is compared with a group of disease negative individuals (the "control" group).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The control group should ideally come from the same population that gave rise to the cases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The case-control study looks back through time at potential exposures that both groups (cases and controls) may have encountered.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A 2×2 table is constructed, displaying exposed cases (A), exposed controls (B), unexposed cases (C) and unexposed controls (D).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The statistic generated to measure association is the odds ratio (OR), which is the ratio of the odds of exposure in the cases (A/C) to the odds of exposure in the controls (B/D), i.e.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] If the OR is significantly greater than 1, then the conclusion is "those with the disease are more likely to have been exposed", whereas if it is close to 1 then the exposure and disease are not likely associated.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] If the OR is far less than one, then this suggests that the exposure is a protective factor in the causation of the disease.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Case-control studies are usually faster and more cost-effective than cohort studies but are sensitive to bias (such as recall bias and selection bias).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The main challenge is to identify the appropriate control group; the distribution of exposure among the control group should be representative of the distribution in the population that gave rise to the cases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This can be achieved by drawing a random sample from the original population at risk.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This has as a consequence that the control group can contain people with the disease under study when the disease has a high attack rate in a population.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] where N is the ratio of cases to controls.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] As the odds ratio approaches 1, the number of cases required for statistical significance grows towards infinity; rendering case-control studies all but useless for low odds ratios.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Cohort studies select subjects based on their exposure status.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The study subjects should be at risk of the outcome under investigation at the beginning of the cohort study; this usually means that they should be disease free when the cohort study starts.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The cohort is followed through time to assess their later outcome status.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] An example of a cohort study would be the investigation of a cohort of smokers and non-smokers over time to estimate the incidence of lung cancer.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The same 2×2 table is constructed as with the case control study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, the point estimate generated is the relative risk (RR), which is the probability of disease for a person in the exposed group, *P*e = *A* / (*A* + *B*) over the probability of disease for a person in the unexposed group, *P**u* = *C* / (*C* + *D*), i.e.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Prospective studies have many benefits over case control studies.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The RR is a more powerful effect measure than the OR, as the OR is just an estimation of the RR, since true incidence cannot be calculated in a case control study where subjects are selected based on disease status.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Temporality can be established in a prospective study, and confounders are more easily controlled for.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, they are more costly, and there is a greater chance of losing subjects to follow-up based on the long time period over which the cohort is followed.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Cohort studies also are limited by the same equation for number of cases as for cohort studies, but, if the base incidence rate in the study population is very low, the number of cases required is reduced by 1⁄2.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Although epidemiology is sometimes viewed as a collection of statistical tools used to elucidate the associations of exposures to health outcomes, a deeper understanding of this science is that of discovering *causal* relationships.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] "Correlation does not imply causation" is a common theme for much of the epidemiological literature.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] For epidemiologists, the key is in the term inference.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Correlation, or at least association between two variables, is a necessary but not sufficient criterion for the inference that one variable causes the other.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists use gathered data and a broad range of biomedical and psychosocial theories in an iterative way to generate or expand theory, to test hypotheses, and to make educated, informed assertions about which relationships are causal, and about exactly how they are causal.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists emphasize that the "**one cause – one effect**" understanding is a simplistic mis-belief.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Most outcomes, whether disease or death, are caused by a chain or web consisting of many component causes.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Causes can be distinguished as necessary, sufficient or probabilistic conditions.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] If a necessary condition can be identified and controlled (e.g., antibodies to a disease agent, energy in an injury), the harmful outcome can be avoided (Robertson, 2015).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] One tool regularly used to conceptualize the multicausality associated with disease is the causal pie model.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In 1965, Austin Bradford Hill proposed a series of considerations to help assess evidence of causation, which have come to be commonly known as the "Bradford Hill criteria".
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In contrast to the explicit intentions of their author, Hill's considerations are now sometimes taught as a checklist to be implemented for assessing causality.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Consistency of Data**: Consistent findings observed by different persons in different places with different samples strengthens the likelihood of an effect.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Specificity**: Causation is likely if a very specific population at a specific site and disease with no other likely explanation.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The more specific an association between a factor and an effect is, the bigger the probability of a causal relationship.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Temporality**: The effect has to occur after the cause (and if there is an expected delay between the cause and expected effect, then the effect must occur after that delay).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Biological gradient**: Greater exposure should generally lead to greater incidence of the effect.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, in some cases, the mere presence of the factor can trigger the effect.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In other cases, an inverse proportion is observed: greater exposure leads to lower incidence.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Plausibility**: A plausible mechanism between cause and effect is helpful (but Hill noted that knowledge of the mechanism is limited by current knowledge).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Coherence**: Coherence between epidemiological and laboratory findings increases the likelihood of an effect.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] However, Hill noted that "... lack of such [laboratory] evidence cannot nullify the epidemiological effect on associations".
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Experiment**: "Occasionally it is possible to appeal to experimental evidence".
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] **Analogy**: The effect of similar factors may be considered.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In United States law, epidemiology alone cannot prove that a causal association does not exist in general.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Conversely, it can be (and is in some circumstances) taken by US courts, in an individual case, to justify an inference that a causal association does exist, based upon a balance of probability.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The subdiscipline of forensic epidemiology is directed at the investigation of specific causation of disease or injury in individuals or groups of individuals in instances in which causation is disputed or is unclear, for presentation in legal settings.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiological practice and the results of epidemiological analysis make a significant contribution to emerging population-based health management frameworks.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Examples of organizations that use population-based health management that leverage the work and results of epidemiological practice include Canadian Strategy for Cancer Control, Health Canada Tobacco Control Programs, Rick Hansen Foundation, Canadian Tobacco Control Research Initiative.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Applied epidemiology is the practice of using epidemiological methods to protect or improve the health of a population.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] As the surveillance and reporting of diseases and other health factors become increasingly difficult in humanitarian crisis situations, the methodologies used to report the data are compromised.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] One study found that less than half (42.4%) of nutrition surveys sampled from humanitarian contexts correctly calculated the prevalence of malnutrition and only one-third (35.3%) of the surveys met the criteria for quality.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Among the mortality surveys, only 3.2% met the criteria for quality.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] As nutritional status and mortality rates help indicate the severity of a crisis, the tracking and reporting of these health factors is crucial.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Vital registries are usually the most effective ways to collect data, but in humanitarian contexts these registries can be non-existent, unreliable, or inaccessible.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] As such, mortality is often inaccurately measured using either prospective demographic surveillance or retrospective mortality surveys.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Prospective demographic surveillance requires much manpower and is difficult to implement in a spread-out population.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Retrospective mortality surveys are prone to selection and reporting biases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Other methods are being developed, but are not common practice yet.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The concept of waves in epidemics has implications especially for communicable diseases.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A working definition for the term "epidemic wave" is based on two key features: 1) it comprises periods of upward or downward trends, and 2) these increases or decreases must be substantial and sustained over a period of time, in order to distinguish them from minor fluctuations or reporting errors.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The use of a consistent scientific definition is to provide a consistent language that can be used to communicate about and understand the progression of the COVID-19 pandemic, which would aid healthcare organizations and policymakers in resource planning and allocation.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Different fields in epidemiology have different levels of validity.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] One way to assess the validity of findings is the ratio of false-positives (claimed effects that are not correct) to false-negatives (studies which fail to support a true effect).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In genetic epidemiology, candidate-gene studies may produce over 100 false-positive findings for each false-negative.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] By contrast genome-wide association appear close to the reverse, with only one false positive for every 100 or more false-negatives.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This ratio has improved over time in genetic epidemiology, as the field has adopted stringent criteria.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] By contrast, other epidemiological fields have not required such rigorous reporting and are much less reliable as a result.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Random error is the result of fluctuations around a true value because of sampling variability.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] It can occur during data collection, coding, transfer, or analysis.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Examples of random errors include poorly worded questions, a misunderstanding in interpreting an individual answer from a particular respondent, or a typographical error during coding.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Random error affects measurement in a transient, inconsistent manner and it is impossible to correct for random error.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] There is a random error in all sampling procedures – sampling error.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Precision in epidemiological variables is a measure of random error.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Precision is also inversely related to random error, so that to reduce random error is to increase precision.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Confidence intervals are computed to demonstrate the precision of relative risk estimates.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The narrower the confidence interval, the more precise the relative risk estimate.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] There are two basic ways to reduce random error in an epidemiological study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The first is to increase the sample size of the study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In other words, add more subjects to your study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The second is to reduce the variability in measurement in the study.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] This might be accomplished by using a more precise measuring device or by increasing the number of measurements.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Note, that if sample size or number of measurements are increased, or a more precise measuring tool is purchased, the costs of the study are usually increased.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] There is usually an uneasy balance between the need for adequate precision and the practical issue of study cost.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A systematic error or bias occurs when there is a difference between the true value (in the population) and the observed value (in the study) from any cause other than sampling variability.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] An example of systematic error is if, unknown to you, the pulse oximeter you are using is set incorrectly and adds two points to the true value each time a measurement is taken.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The measuring device could be precise but not accurate.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Because the error happens in every instance, it is systematic.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Conclusions you draw based on that data will still be incorrect.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] But the error can be reproduced in the future (e.g., by using the same mis-set instrument).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A mistake in coding that affects *all* responses for that particular question is another example of a systematic error.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The validity of a study is dependent on the degree of systematic error.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Selection bias occurs when study subjects are selected or become part of the study as a result of a third, unmeasured variable which is associated with both the exposure and outcome of interest.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] For instance, it has repeatedly been noted that cigarette smokers and non smokers tend to differ in their study participation rates.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] (Sackett D cites the example of Seltzer et al., in which 85% of non smokers and 67% of smokers returned mailed questionnaires.) Such a difference in response will not lead to bias if it is not also associated with a systematic difference in outcome between the two response groups.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Information bias is bias arising from systematic error in the assessment of a variable.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In this example, recall bias probably occurred as a result of women who had had miscarriages having an apparent tendency to better recall and therefore report previous exposures.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Next to sample- and variable-related bias, bias can also arise from an imperfect study design.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] One example is immortal time bias, where during study period, there is some interval during which the outcome event cannot occur (making these individual "immortal").
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Confounding has traditionally been defined as bias arising from the co-occurrence or mixing of effects of extraneous factors, referred to as confounders, with the main effect(s) of interest.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] A more recent definition of confounding invokes the notion of *counterfactual* effects.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] According to this view, when one observes an outcome of interest, say Y=1 (as opposed to Y=0), in a given population A which is entirely exposed (i.e. exposure *X* = 1 for every unit of the population) the risk of this event will be *R*A1.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The counterfactual or unobserved risk *R*A0 corresponds to the risk which would have been observed if these same individuals had been unexposed (i.e.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] *X* = 0 for every unit of the population).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] The true effect of exposure therefore is: *R*A1 − *R*A0 (if one is interested in risk differences) or *R*A1/*R*A0 (if one is interested in relative risk).
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Since the counterfactual risk *R*A0 is unobservable we approximate it using a second population B and we actually measure the following relations: *R*A1 − *R*B0 or *R*A1/*R*B0.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In this situation, confounding occurs when *R*A0 ≠ *R*B0.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Some epidemiologists prefer to think of confounding separately from common categorizations of bias since, unlike selection and information bias, confounding stems from real causal effects.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Few universities have offered epidemiology as a course of study at the undergraduate level.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] An undergraduate program exists at Johns Hopkins University in which students who major in public health can take graduate-level courses—including epidemiology—during their senior year at the Bloomberg School of Public Health.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] In addition to its master's and doctoral degrees in epidemiology, the University of Michigan School of Public Health has offered undergraduate degree programs since 2017 that include coursework in epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] As public health practitioners, epidemiologists work in a number of different settings.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Some epidemiologists work "in the field" (i.e., in the community; commonly in a public health service), and are often at the forefront of investigating and combating disease outbreaks.
[src:epidemiology/epidemiology] Epidemiologists can also work in for-profit organizations (e.g., pharmaceutical and medical device companies) in groups such as market research or clinical development.
